<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 16 日，星期日 09:32:24 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Pulls Back From Humanitarian Cooperation at U.N.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>莫斯科结束叙利亚援助走廊并可能阻止更新黑海粮食协议<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057849"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817814?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">外交官和分析人士表示，俄罗斯总统弗拉基米尔·普京似乎愿意打破粮食协议等协议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历山大·卡扎科夫/克里姆林宫/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057849"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-mauldin" itemprop="url" rel="author">威廉·莫尔丁</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 16 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-pulls-back-from-humanitarian-cooperation-at-u-n-a871ae5d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>西方官员表示，由于克里姆林宫在乌克兰面临着一场艰难的战斗，并且在最近国内不稳定的情况下渴望获得国内的支持，俄罗斯准备结束其在联合国关键人道主义领域的合作。</p><p>官员们表示，最近几周，俄罗斯一直在推动从马里撤走联合国维和行动，封锁了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-vetoes-u-n-measure-on-cross-border-aid-to-northern-syria-11657301536?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">联合国对叙利亚的一条重要援助供应线</a>，现在还威胁要终止一项允许乌克兰恢复<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-history-museum-in-recaptured-ukrainian-city-28746610?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">黑海谷物出口的</a>协议。</p><p>莫斯科在联合国重新进行赤裸裸的外交努力之际，俄罗斯正面临一场看不到尽头的乌克兰战争，几周前瓦格纳集团发生了武装叛乱，这对俄罗斯总统构成了十多年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-turmoil-shows-a-forever-war-in-ukraine-hurts-putin-5cbb8738?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最严重的挑战</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>对权力的掌控。</p><p>美俄关系分析师迪米特里·西姆斯表示：“俄罗斯精英和广大俄罗斯民众认为，政府做出了太多让步，而他们却没有得到太多回报。”粮食交易定于周一结束。</p><p>去年7月在伊斯坦布尔签署的黑海粮食倡议是战争期间为数不多的外交突破之一，使乌克兰能够向世界各地出口超过3200万吨小麦、玉米、葵花籽油和其他商品。该协议在黑海开辟了一条特别的海上走廊，供联合国使用商船和包租船将乌克兰粮食运送到苏丹、也门和索马里等受危机影响的国家。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817812?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷物在乌克兰港口装载。粮食协议是战争期间为数不多的外交突破之一。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安德鲁·克拉夫琴科/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国官员和西方外交官表示，土耳其政府与联合国一起帮助促成了最初的协议，过去一年里，土耳其政府在阻止俄罗斯违反协议方面发挥了核心作用。土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安最近几周再次表达了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkeys-double-dealing-in-the-ukraine-war-345dbfdf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与西方合作的意愿</a>，同意在长达一年的僵局后为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sweden-races-to-secure-turkish-support-for-nato-bid-2452c14f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">瑞典加入北约开绿灯</a>。</p><p>埃尔多安周五表示，他和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkeys-economic-troubles-force-erdogan-to-tilt-away-from-putin-9006b5a3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">普京在延长协议方面意见“一致”</a> ，但没有详细说明。克里姆林宫发言人德米特里·佩斯科夫告诉记者，莫斯科仍在权衡这个问题。</p><p>美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯周五在印度尼西亚雅加达举行的一次集会上表示：“如果莫斯科兑现其威胁，包括该地区在内的发展中国家将付出代价，包括食品价格上涨和粮食短缺加剧。”</p><p>俄罗斯过去曾威胁要取消该协议，并在去年10月乌克兰袭击其驻克里米亚军队后短暂中止了与该协议的合作。乌克兰和美国官员表示，他们担心俄罗斯越来越愿意退出该协议，因为普京在国际上日益孤立，国内不稳定。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>联合国安理会成员国应该如何与俄罗斯在全球问题上合作？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>一位美国官员表示，克里姆林宫可能正在评估粮食协议的成本和收益转移，越来越多的人担心，对乌克兰施加的经济压力可能会超过终止协议的外交影响，特别是在俄罗斯国内存在不确定性的情况下。</p><p>联合国秘书长安东尼奥·古特雷斯上周写信给普京，提议乌克兰继续出口粮食，以换取俄罗斯农业银行的一家子公司与环球银行间金融合作银行国际支付系统重新连接。</p><p>在纽约，俄罗斯几十年来一直利用其作为联合国安理会五个拥有否决权的成员国之一的影响力向西方和其他反对者施加压力，但外交官和分析人士表示，普京现在似乎异常愿意打破过去的协议例如粮食协议和叙利亚援助生命线。</p><p> “俄罗斯已经从脾气暴躁的迁就姿态转变为全面阻挠，”监测冲突的非营利组织国际危机组织的联合国主任理查德·高恩说。</p><p>俄罗斯驻联合国代表团没有回复置评请求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817816?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">二月份，卡车满载联合国向叙利亚提供的物资。俄罗斯最近封锁了联合国对该国的援助供应线。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ghaith Alsayed/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>俄罗斯于 7 月 11 日否决了联合国安理会一项决议，该决议要求人道主义组织向叛军控制的叙利亚境内超过 400 万人提供食品、水和药品。俄罗斯表示不愿就这一问题进行谈判达成妥协，并敦促联合国接受叙利亚政府的提议，要求其控制土耳其的援助运送。</p><p>如果联合国接受这一提议，这将有效地结束近十年来的努力，通过这一努力，该国际机构能够在不寻求大马士革批准的情况下向叙利亚叛军控制的地区提供援助。叙利亚总统巴沙尔·阿萨德长期以来一直试图切断对该国反对派控制地区的粮食和其他供应，试图剥夺叛乱分子的民众支持。</p><p>华盛顿战略与国际研究中心高级研究员娜塔莎·霍尔表示，普京正在“提醒世界，如果他愿意，他可以让世界着火”。</p><p>写信给 Jared Malsin <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(jared.malsin@wsj.com)</a>和 William Mauldin ( <a href="mailto:william.mauldin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">william.mauldin@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/Russia-pulls-back-from-人道主义-合作-at-un-a871ae5d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/Russia-pulls-back-from-人道主义-合作-at-un-a871ae5d<author><![CDATA[Jared MalsinWilliam Mauldin]]></author><category>乌克兰危机</category><category>食品/饮料</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>消费品</category><category>食物产品</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>发展/人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>乌克兰危机</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>发展</category><category>人道主义援助</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>食物</category><category>饮料</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>消费品</category><category>食物产品</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Pope Francis Accepts Bishop Unilaterally Installed by China]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>梵蒂冈称北京此举违反了2018年主教任命协议的精神<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057830"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="562" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817870?width=860&amp;height=562" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">教宗方济各表示，与北京达成的协议让他在任命中国主教方面拥有最终决定权。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Riccardo Antimiani/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057830"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/francis-x-rocca" itemprop="url" rel="author">弗朗西斯·X·罗卡</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 15 日上午 10:48 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pope-francis-accepts-bishop-unilaterally-installed-by-china-9eec803e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>罗马——教宗方济各接受中国当局在未与梵蒂冈协商的情况下任命的一名男子为上海主教，这是教宗决心在中国收紧宗教限制的情况下寻求与北京和解的最新迹象。</p><p>梵蒂冈周六宣布，教宗方济各任命沉斌主教为上海教区领导，距离中国天主教当局宣布他已正式就任这一职位已过去三个多月。</p><p>梵蒂冈国务卿红衣主教彼得罗·帕罗林告诉梵蒂冈媒体，教宗的行为是为了“教区的更大利益以及主教牧灵工作的富有成果”，但他表示，北京单方面决定将主教从前任主教手中调离。海门教区的做法违反了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vatican-and-china-agree-deal-over-bishops-allowing-pope-a-veto-1537613087?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2018年关于主教任命的权力分享协议</a>的“对话与合作精神”。</p><p>中国外交部周六没有立即回应置评请求。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>据估计，中国有 10 至 1200 万天主教徒，几十年来一直分为在政府注册的“爱国”教会和拒绝政府控制的所谓地下教会。自 1949 年共产主义革命后不久，梵蒂冈和中国就没有建立外交关系。</p><p> 2018年，梵蒂冈和北京签署了一项协议，并于2020年和2022年续签<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vatican-and-china-renew-agreement-on-bishops-as-beijing-tightens-control-of-religion-11666436864?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，任期两年</a>，赋予双方在主教任命方面的发言权。</p><p>该协议标志着教皇对其任命主教的特权做出了罕见的让步，梵蒂冈官员认为，这对于维护中国教会的团结是必要的。包括香港前主教陈日君枢机在内的批评者认为，该协议是对该国忠于教皇的地下天主教徒的背叛。</p><p>该交易的细节仍然保密，但教皇方济各表示，这让他拥有最终决定权。</p><p>这笔交易是在习近平领导下的中国共产党达成的</p>政府加强了对包括天主教会在内的宗教的控制。<p></p><p>宗教团体被要求根据共产党的教义修改其实践和教义，并通过“中国化”过程发展习近平所说的“有中国特色的社会主义宗教理论”。</p><p>梵蒂冈承认，迄今为止该协议的成果微乎其微。自2018年以来，根据该协议任命的中国新主教屈指可数。</p><p>去年11月， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/vatican-says-china-broke-agreement-on-bishops-11669480974?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">梵蒂冈指责北京</a>转让彭伟昭主教违反协议</p>他从梵蒂冈批准的余江主教职位调任为江西教区辅理主教，而江西教区并未得到梵蒂冈的承认。<p></p><p>周六，梵蒂冈对上海任命的反应较为温和。帕罗林枢机主教表示，该案的某些方面可能是未公布的协议未预见到的，需要进一步谈判。他还称赞沉主教是一位“令人尊敬的牧师”。但他表示，在中国的所有主教任命，包括调职，都必须由罗马和北京协商一致作出，这是“必不可少的”。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——新加坡的 Chun Han Wong 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Francis X. Rocca： <a href="mailto:francis.rocca@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">francis.rocca@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bf4d14ac-311a-4b61-9cc1-ce0772d8de02.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 14:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pope-francis-accepts-bishop-unisidely-installed-by-china-9eec803e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pope-francis-accepts-bishop-unisidely-installed-by-china-9eec803e<author><![CDATA[Francis X. Rocca]]></author><category>宗教</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>宗教</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>方济各</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Global Migration Boom Keeps Housing Costs High]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>移民激增正在推高租金并支撑房价，使通胀逃亡变得更加复杂<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057457"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815812?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">截至 6 月份的 12 个月内，澳大利亚主要城市的平均租金上涨了 11.5%。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Brent Lewin/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001057457"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stuart-condie" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯图尔特·康迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 15 日上午 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>悉尼——富裕国家的移民浪潮正在增加住房成本的上行压力，令租房者和购房者感到沮丧，并使央行官员更难抑制通胀。</p><p>从欧洲到亚洲和北美，受劳动力市场紧张和新冠疫情后宽松的旅行规定的吸引，人们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-biggest-economies-cautiously-open-their-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-664c3549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">跨境流动的人数创历史新高</a>。许多人登陆住房供应短缺的城市。</p><p>尽管借贷成本急剧上升，尤其是在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canadas-immigration-problem-not-enough-homes-for-newcomers-11665144002" target="_blank" class="icon none">欧洲、加拿大和澳大利亚</a>，这有助于推高租金并防止房价下跌至预期水平。</p><p>加拿大去年吸收了创纪录的 437,000 名移民，房价在连续 10 个月下跌后，从 2 月份开始再次上涨。在英国，5 月份的年度租金通胀率达到 2016 年有记录以来的最高水平，并且在过去 21 个月中有 20 个月加速增长。</p><p>在美国， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">租金增长正在放缓</a>，但房价在过去一年下跌后又开始上涨。根据全国房地产经纪人协会的数据，美国现有房屋销售价格中位数在 1 月份触底至 361,200 美元，此后每个月都在上涨，但仍同比下降。</p><p>租金和住房成本<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/inflations-fall-from-a-four-decade-high-in-four-charts-b8612f5f?mod=hp_major_pos2#cxrecs_s" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">仍然是美国通胀的推动因素</a>，占 6 月份消费者价格上涨 0.2% 的 70%。</p><p>许多因素，包括新房供应投资不足，以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/low-mortgage-rates-home-sales-low-supply-899aab29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">一些业主不愿出售</a>，都导致美国住房成本居高不下。不过，一些经济学家表示，如此多的合法和非法移民的到来也是原因之一。去年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-population-growth-remains-sluggish-despite-uptick-this-year-11671723045" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">美国人口增长</a>了 126 万人，这是自 2019 年以来最快的增速，其中几乎全部增长（100 万人）都来自移民。</p><p>高盛最近的一份报告指出，移民是主要经济体房价在加息引发的下跌后出现稳定迹象且高于预期的一个关键原因。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815817?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在加拿大，房地产价格在连续 10 个月下跌后，于 2 月份再次开始上涨。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：格雷厄姆休斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>经济学家约瑟夫·布里格斯（Joseph Briggs）和乔瓦尼·皮尔多梅尼科（Giovanni Pierdomenico）写道：“疫情后移民的复苏似乎正在促进人口增长，从而提高住房需求并限制房价下跌。”他们写道，澳大利亚和加拿大的房价涨幅最大，这两个国家的移民和人口增长反弹最为强劲。</p><p>对于业主和房东来说，移民的支持是个好消息，可以限制经济增长放缓带来的负面影响。住房成本大幅下降（如果利率持续攀升，这种情况仍有可能发生）将破坏世界经济的稳定。</p><p>但对许多人来说，持续居高不下的住房成本令人沮丧，尤其是在许多其他费用不断上涨的情况下。</p><p>斯科特·威尔逊 (Scott) 和黛安·威尔逊 (Dianne Wilson) 与两个年幼的儿子最终决定带着两个年幼的儿子从英国搬到澳大利亚布里斯班，威尔逊女士在那里找到了一名儿童保育教育工作者的工作，他们目睹了 2023 年租金的上涨。他们希望在 8 月份搬家，并考虑每月支付 2,000 美元购买一套家庭住宅，他们的搬迁代理告诉他们，去年的费用约为 1,400 美元。</p><p> “大部分的内容都已经非常非常过时了。我只能将它们描述为 20 世纪 70 年代的风格，”Wilson 说道，并引用了配有牛油果绿色台面的厨房。这对夫妇正在网上搜索犯罪统计数据，以确定更便宜但仍然宜居的社区。</p><p>由于住房成本（尤其是租金）构成央行通胀指标的重要组成部分，其粘性为进一步加息的论点增添了支撑。</p><p>澳大利亚和加拿大央行最近的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-canada-lifts-interest-rates-warns-path-to-stable-inflation-at-risk-18462fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">加息令投资者感到惊讶</a>。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》最近报道，去年移居富裕国家的人数比离开富裕国家的人数多了约 500 万人，比疫情前的水平增加了 80%。德国、加拿大、日本和其他国家正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/even-japan-wants-more-foreign-workers-and-it-is-letting-them-stay-for-good-3628a145?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">重写移民规则</a>，以引进更多人才来填补技能短缺。</p><p>经济学家估计，大约 85% 的移民在抵达一个国家后成为租户，这意味着他们对住房成本的压力在租赁市场上是最大的，尽管有些人最终还是购买了住房。</p><p>澳大利亚在疫情期间基本上关闭了边境，根据官方预测，截至 6 月的 12 个月内，抵达澳大利亚的人数比离开的人数多了约 40 万人，几乎是疫情前平均水平的两倍。官员们预计，截至 2024 年 6 月的 12 个月内，这个人口约 2600 万的国家将新增 315,000 名移民。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815815?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">菲利普·洛 (Philip Lowe)，澳大利亚储备银行行长</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：希拉里·沃德/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>随着移民寻找住处，大量涌入促使澳大利亚央行行长菲利普·洛(Philip Lowe)在五月份对通货膨胀发出警报。</p><p>根据房地产分析提供商 CoreLogic 的数据，截至 6 月份的 12 个月里，澳大利亚主要城市的平均租金上涨了 11.5%，比疫情前的水平上涨了 25% 以上。房价在截至 2 月份的七个月里下跌 9.1% 后，最近又开始环比上涨。</p><p> “今年人口增长了 2%。还有2%的房子吗？不，”洛说。</p><p>澳大利亚房地产经纪人表示，最近看房的队伍常常排得很长，以至于许多潜在的租户甚至还没进去就走开了。他们预计，随着北半球学年结束后海外学生的到来，房地产需求将再次激增。</p><p> “我真的不知道要把它们安置在哪里，”在悉尼从事房地产工作的戴安娜·韦西奥 (Diana Vescio) 说。</p><p>韦西奥表示，一些房东提高了租金，以弥补疫情最严重时损失的资金。他回忆起一段时期，一些租户违约、协商降低租金或搬到更便宜的地方。她说，其他人正在努力偿还住房贷款，但住房贷款的成本已经增加。</p><p>当澳大利亚储备银行于 2022 年 5 月开始大幅加息计划时，许多经济学家预计澳大利亚房价将下跌 20%。</p><p>相反，在许多移民的登陆点悉尼，房价从近期低点上涨了 6.7%，相当于住宅价值中位数上涨了 45,000 澳元。</p><p>根据澳大利亚房地产分类集团 Domain 的数据，截至 2024 年 6 月的 12 个月里，悉尼的平均房价可能会上涨 6-9%，因为很少有人出售自己的房子，而且该市的人口在增长。报告预测，在澳大利亚各地，移民将推动对 30 万套住房的需求增加。</p><p>移民给住房供应带来的额外压力可能意味着，自 2022 年 5 月以来已将国家现金利率提高 4 个百分点至 11 年来最高水平的储备银行将继续加息。</p><p>汇丰银行(HSBC)经济学家保罗·布洛克瑟姆(Paul Bloxham)表示，“风险在于，这可能会引发通货膨胀，导致货币环境比其他情况更紧缩。”</p><p>在移民增加和建设缓慢的背景下，德国的租金也在上涨。乌克兰战争造成的超过 110 万难民涌入，导致 2022 年净移民人数达到创纪录的 150 万，而政府每年计划建造 40 万套新公寓，以解决住房短缺问题，而该国的建设比例还不到 75%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815818?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">许多经济学家表示，最好的应对措施是加强建设。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛丽亚·费克/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>房地产平台 ImmoScout24 的数据显示，2023 年第一季度德国的年租金增长加速，柏林和斯图加特的季度增长创下历史新高。报告称，该国七个最大城市的租金上涨导致许多潜在租户被迫迁往周边地区。</p><p>许多经济学家认为，最好的应对措施是加强建设。在英国，新建住房供应量于 2020 年达到顶峰，此后一直未能达到政府每年 30 万套新房的目标，部分原因是大流行造成的破坏。</p><p>澳大利亚政府五月份表示，将很快推出税收减免措施，以增加出租住宿的供应，同时提高对低收入群体的租金援助金额。</p><p>但建设可能需要数年时间，部分原因是严格的规划法规。</p><p>写信给 Stuart Condie： <a href="mailto:stuart.condie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stuart.condie@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-migration-boom-keeps-housing-costs-high-5fc84b7f<author><![CDATA[Stuart Condie]]></author><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>房地产</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>房屋销售/住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>房屋销售</category><category>住房负担能力数据</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>房价数据</category><category>房地产市场</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Canada Woos American H-1B Visa Holders Fed Up With U.S. Immigration System]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>向外国人提供工作许可证的举措抓住了科技行业的挫败感<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055729"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816894?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">加拿大提议的工作许可证将允许 H-1B 签证持有者在没有工作的情况下移居该国。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡洛斯·奥索里奥/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055729"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michelle-hackman" itemprop="url" rel="author">米歇尔·哈克曼 (Michelle Hackman)</a></span> ，华盛顿；保罗·维埃拉 ( <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">Paul Vieira)</a></span> ，渥太华</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 15 日上午 8:45 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-u-s-immigration-system-5f7e866d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>本月，加拿大将开始向所有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-layoffs-hit-h1b-visa-workers-hard-ca03c2cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">持有 H-1B 签证的美国移民</a>提供开放工作许可证，此举显然是为了吸引因美国移民程序而受挫的受过高等教育的外国人。</p><p>国际学生和专业人士日益认识到，在竞争日益激烈的签证抽签和不断增加的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-other-immigration-morass-a-battle-over-workers-green-cards-11567828860?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">绿卡积压</a>之间，永久定居美国过于缓慢和困难，这是加拿大最新的努力。</p><p>加拿大上个月在多伦多举行的北美科技会议 Collision 上公布了新的招聘战略，旨在吸引在美国失业的外国科技行业工人，这些工人的移民身份在<a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Farticles%2Ftech-layoffs-hit-h1b-visa-workers-hard-ca03c2cd&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AOvVaw2MMlxA7QeVZdSSGl-wxWnb" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">经历了</a>加拿大移民部长肖恩·弗雷泽表示， <a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Farticles%2Ftech-layoffs-hit-h1b-visa-workers-hard-ca03c2cd&amp;sa=D&amp;sntz=1&amp;usg=AOvVaw2MMlxA7QeVZdSSGl-wxWnb" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">最近发生了一系列裁员</a>。</p><p>几十年来，就读美国大学并在美国永久定居一直是全球许多雄心勃勃的年轻外国人的圣杯。但这条老路已经开始磨损。国际学生可以凭学生签证工作一到三年，但此后转为工作签证（最常见的是高技能外国人的 H-1B）最近变得更具竞争力。去年，大约五分之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-says-some-companies-cheat-h-1b-lottery-driving-record-applications-1a3e4fd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的年度 H-1B 抽签</a>申请获得了签证；今年这个数字接近十分之一。</p><p>美国前外交官、Argo Visa 联合创始人克里斯·理查森 (Chris Richardson) 表示：“随着 H-1B 抽签情况逐年恶化，对于许多人来说，加拿大实际上可能是他们唯一的选择。”申请人的美国签证流程。</p><p>加拿大提议的工作许可证将允许 H-1B 签证持有者在没有工作的情况下移居加拿大，并在抵达后寻找工作。加拿大专家表示，符合该计划资格的移民类型也可能很快成为该国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/report-cites-canadas-immigration-system-as-role-model-11565701200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">积分移民制度</a>下的永久居民。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6E29A9EF-6E10-45CB-BB21-F8C28BC8FA84&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcanada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-u-s-immigration-system-5f7e866d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">席卷科技行业的裁员也未能幸免持有临时签证（即 H1B）的工人。在被迫离开该国之前，他们只有 60 天的时间寻找新的签证担保职位。主持人佐伊·托马斯 (Zoe Thomas) 与一名面临这一挑战的工人以及《华尔街日报》记者陈德平 (Te-Ping Chen) 讨论了更广泛的影响。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>如果没有快速通道计划，他们要么需要根据加拿大的常规程序申请入境，要么需要加拿大雇主为他们获得工作许可证。</p><p>弗雷泽在会上表示，这种情况为加拿大提供了机会。</p><p> “有很多人在他们的职业生涯中可能没有考虑过来加拿大，但非常想留在北美市场，”他说。</p><p>从英国到澳大利亚的英语国家都受益于外国人对缓慢且看似反复无常的美国移民制度的不满， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/border-arrests-have-dropped-70-since-title-42-ended-biden-administration-says-3d00dc48?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">从英国到澳大利亚的大学</a>都吸引了更多来自中国和印度等国家的国际学生。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>美国如何才能在吸引和留住受过高等教育的外国人方面更好地与加拿大竞争？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>研究移民趋势的移民律师、加拿大官员和政策分析师表示，加拿大被认为是理想的目的地，因为根据过去 15 年修订的规定，国际学生毕业后可以更轻松地获得永久居留权。如果他们最终为美国公司工作，他们可以与同事生活在同一时区。近年来，越来越多的美国公司，如微软、谷歌等，在多伦多、温哥华等加拿大城市设立了分支机构。</p><p>对于从印度到美国的移民来说，他们在科技公司招聘的人员中所占比例过高， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/some-100-000-green-cards-at-risk-of-going-to-waste-in-covid-19-backlog-11628080201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">成为永久居民的过程</a>被证明是特别令人烦恼的。这是因为美国限制了向任何一种国籍的申请人颁发的就业担保绿卡的数量，而每年申请绿卡的印度人数量远远多于可供他们使用的绿卡数量。如果没有国会的干预，新申请永久居留权的印度人可能会在叫号之前死亡。</p><p> Ketaki Desai 于 2002 年移居美国攻读博士学位。她拥有生物医学科学博士学位，并于 2008 年首次与丈夫申请绿卡。到 2020 年，绿卡仍未获得批准，而且由于新冠病毒相关的处理延误，她现有的签证即将到期。德赛受够了，辞去了在匹兹堡大学医学中心帮助管理 10 亿美元生命科学基金的工作，举家搬到了多伦多。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816898?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ketaki Desai 和她的丈夫在多伦多的家中。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：凯塔基·德赛</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“我感到非常沮丧和愤怒，”德赛回忆道。 “当我们意识到我们可以从加拿大永久居留权开始时，这是理所当然的。”</p><p>她在安大略省运营的一家初创基金担任高管，一年前，她离开公司，创办了自己的科技公司，为有特殊需要的儿童开发数字工具。今年，她和她的家人将成为加拿大公民。</p><p>华盛顿智囊团美国政策国家基金会对加拿大移民数据的分析显示，过去十年印度向加拿大的移民数量几乎翻了两番。</p><p>鉴于劳动力老龄化，加拿大正在做出更广泛的努力，利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canadas-immigration-problem-not-enough-homes-for-newcomers-11665144002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">移民作为经济工具</a>来填补整个经济领域的职位空缺，并推动经济增长。加拿大科技行业领导者估计，从软件工程师到编码员再到计算机科学家，明年的工人短缺人数可能达到 25 万人。</p><p>加拿大科技公司贸易组织加拿大创新者委员会主席本杰明·伯根表示：“政府正在尝试利用所有可以利用的手段来缩小这一差距。”</p><p>为了吸引未来的科技行业工人，加拿大最近提供的另一个胡萝卜是让外国学生更容易成为永久居民。自2008年以来，加拿大对移民规则进行了修改，其中包括允许国际学生毕业后获得三年期工作许可证，并在学年和假期期间在校外工作，无需许可证。当时，加拿大官员表示，目标是留住外国毕业生，因为他们熟悉加拿大社会以及对经济的潜在贡献。</p><p>结果是：加拿大学院和大学的国际学生入学人数激增。根据加拿大统计局的数据，2000年，加拿大有122,000名学习许可持有者。加拿大统计局的最新数据显示，这一数字已激增至约 620,000 人。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="457" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816880?width=700&amp;height=457" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">蒙特利尔麦吉尔大学。近年来，加拿大学院和大学的国际学生入学人数激增。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼尔·斯利姆/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“如果我是美国政府，我会对加拿大基本上吸走美国工人感到非常沮丧，”多伦多移民律师塞尔吉奥·卡拉斯(Sergio Karas)说，他与公司合作，帮助确保海外工人的安全。</p><p>但加拿大在一个领域还无法竞争：工资。任仕达的一项分析显示，虽然技术人员的工资高于全国平均水平，但与美国类似职位的员工获得的薪酬相比，还是相形见绌，而且许多加拿大技术工人最终离开加拿大，到国外寻找更高薪的职位。一家全球人力资源咨询公司。</p><p>目前，许多离开美国前往加拿大的移民认为这是暂时的举动。</p><p> “对于科技工作者来说，美国是圣杯。更多的钱，更多的可能性，更多的一切。卡拉斯说，就大型跨国公司的机会而言，加拿大非常有限。</p><p>就连德赛也在考虑返回匹兹堡的选择，即使是持临时签证。</p><p> “我们永远是加拿大人，因为当美国不在时，加拿大就在我们身边，”她说。 “但我们想念匹兹堡的社区。”</p><p>写信给 Michelle Hackman <a href="mailto:michelle.hackman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（michelle.hackman@wsj.com）</a>和 Paul Vieira（ <a href="mailto:Paul.Vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Paul.Vieira@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 12:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-us-immigration-system-5f7e866d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-woos-american-h-1b-visa-holders-fed-up-with-us-immigration-system-5f7e866d<author><![CDATA[Michelle HackmanPaul Vieira]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>肖恩·弗雷泽</category><category>克里斯·理查森</category><category>本杰明·伯根</category><category>德赛克塔基</category><category>塞尔吉奥·卡拉斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Six Exercises for Better Balance From a Trainer Who Lives on a Paddleboard]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这种以核心为重点的锻炼可以帮助您在水面或水面上保持稳定的双脚<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-813684/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="苏西·库尼 (Suzie Cooney) 是夏威夷毛伊岛的一名海洋运动表演教练。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>苏西·库尼 (Suzie Cooney) 是夏威夷毛伊岛的一名海洋运动表演教练。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001038828"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001038828"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jen-murphy" itemprop="url" rel="author">珍·墨菲</a></span>| Daeja Fallas 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 15 日上午 6:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/exercises-paddleboard-balance-5e0fdcbb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>如果您在桨板上的平衡能力一般，最糟糕的事情可能就是意外游泳。在陆地上，平衡不良的影响要严重得多，尤其是随着年龄的增长。</p><p>根据美国疾病控制与预防中心的数据，跌倒是 65 岁及以上美国人<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/injury/features/older-adult-falls/index.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">受伤和受伤相关死亡</a>的主要原因。研究表明，我们的平衡能力<a href="https://academic.oup.com/biomedgerontology/article/72/4/572/2629941" target="_blank" class="icon none">从 50 岁左右开始</a>下降。但跌倒并不一定是衰老过程中不可避免的一部分。</p><p>夏威夷毛伊岛专门从事海洋运动的私人教练苏西·库尼 (Suzie Cooney) 表示：“尽早将平衡训练纳入您的健身计划中，实际上可以让您免去急诊室的麻烦。”</p><p>强大的核心有助于我们保持脚步稳定。这组肌肉——腹部肌肉，加上脊柱、骨盆、臀部和躯干两侧的肌肉——为我们的四肢提供力量，同时稳定身体。</p><p>当库尼训练像 2022 年站立划桨世界冠军康纳·巴克斯特这样的运动员时，她会通过本体感觉训练来补充核心训练。本体感觉是身体在不断变化的环境中感知其方向的能力。</p><p>在划桨时，这意味着当平静的水面变成巨浪时要保持力量和稳定性。在日常生活中，它意味着当人行道不平坦时避免绊倒。</p><p>以下六个练习将增强你的核心力量<em>&nbsp;</em>力量，同时提高你的平衡能力。与任何新的锻炼一样，如果您有疼痛或受伤，请咨询您的医生；如果您感到疼痛，请停止。</p><h3>单腿平衡</h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-813733?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">库尼进行单腿平衡。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><strong>原因：</strong> 《英国运动医学杂志》2022 年发表的一项研究表明，中年至晚年无法用单腿保持平衡 10 秒，会导致未来十年内全因<a href="https://bjsm.bmj.com/content/56/17/975" target="_blank" class="icon none">死亡的风险增加</a>近一倍。您可以在刷牙或看电视时进行这个简单的平衡练习。<br><strong>方法：</strong>双脚分开与臀部同宽站立。将左脚离开地板时保持右脚平衡。从悬停开始。最终将左膝置于臀部高度以下。保持臀部平直，眼睛注视前方稳定的物体。如果您需要帮助，请站在椅子或墙壁附近，并用指尖作为灯光辅助。保持 10 到 15 秒。每条腿完成 3 次。<strong><br>选项：</strong>通过站在不稳定的表面（例如 BOSU 球或枕头）上来增加挑战。逐渐在你面前弹起网球并在保持平衡的情况下接住它。接下来，尝试将悬停的脚移至您的前方、侧面和后方，同时保持臀部呈直角。最高级的进展是闭上眼睛执行这些变化。</p><h3>单膝平衡</h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814646?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cooney performs a single-knee balance on a BOSU ball.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <strong>Why:</strong> This exercise strengthens the hips, glutes, lower back, abdominals and the deep pelvic floor muscles.<br> <strong>How:</strong> Center your right knee atop a BOSU ball. Your left knee can rest next to it at hip width. The right foot should hover off the ground behind you. If you have trouble balancing, place it on the floor. Slowly lift the left knee and extend the foot out to the left side. It is normal for the leg to swing around as your brain tries to find a sweet spot. Keep the right hip above the right knee and a tall spine. Extend your arms out for balance. Hold for 15 to 30 seconds. Repeat on the other side.<br> <strong>Options:</strong> A stack of firm pillows or a firm bed mattress can replace a BOSU ball.</p><h3> Stability ball bridge </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814328?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cooney does a stability ball bridge.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <strong>Why:</strong> If you sit all day, this is a great exercise to stretch the hip flexors while strengthening the glutes, hamstrings and core. <strong><br>How:</strong> Select a stability ball suitable to your height. You should be able to sit on the ball with your knees bent at a 90-degree angle or slightly less. Sit on the ball, then walk your feet forward and slowly roll your spine over the ball until only your head and shoulders are supported by the ball and your legs are bent at 90 degrees. Your feet should point straight and be hip-width apart. Rest your hands on your hips. Don&#39;t let your hips sag. Keep a straight line head to knees. Hold for 30 to 60 seconds.<br> <strong>Options:</strong> Challenge yourself by moving your feet closer together, or extend one leg. If you don&#39;t have a ball, you can perform <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/stress-management/multimedia/bridge-pose/vid-20453584" target="_blank" class="icon none">bridge pose</a> with your shoulders on the floor.</p><h3> Single-leg touchdown </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814326?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cooney demonstrates a single-leg touchdown.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <strong>Why:</strong> This balance exercise requires total core strength and targets the glutes, quads, hamstrings and upper back. <strong><br>How:</strong> Stand balanced on your right foot with the right knee slightly bent. Raise the left foot off the ground. The left knee should be in line with the right and bent around 15 to 20 degrees. Engage your abdominal muscles and maintain a straight spine as you bend at the hips and try to touch your left hand to your right toes. Slowly return to start. Perform 10 to 12 reps per side.</p><h3> Stability ball kneeling </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814330?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cooney performs a kneeling balance on a stability ball.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <strong>Why:</strong> This advanced balance and core exercise makes even the legs of pro athletes quiver, Cooney says. “The inner thighs are typically one of the weakest muscle groups in the body, and this exercise will immediately let you know how strong yours are,” she says.<br> <strong>How:</strong> Place both hands flat, around shoulder-width apart, on a stability ball. With legs hip-width apart, allow your knees and upper shins to rest on the ball. Engage your core and slowly draw the knees toward the hands so the feet come off the ground and the knees form a 45-degree angle. Anchor the tops of your feet against the ball for stability. Slowly release your hands and try to rise until you have a slight forward bend at the waist. Keep your eyes gazing forward and use your arms to help you balance. Hold for 30 to 60 seconds.<br> <strong>Options:</strong> If you have never tried this exercise, place the stability ball close to a sturdy surface like a table and use one or both hands for stability.</p><h3> Surf-stance balance squats </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-814329?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cooney does surf-stance balance squats.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <strong>Why: “</strong> Landlocked wannabe surfers, this exercise is for you,” Cooney says. <strong>&nbsp;</strong> Whether you are surfing monster waves or trying to get toes-on-nose riding smaller waves, this drill will help you build leg and core strength. Both are critical when navigating choppy water and for day-to-day activities like bending down.<br> <strong>How:</strong> This drill requires a BOSU ball and an <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/exercises-across-the-boards-improving-core-strength-as-well-as-balance-1424714512?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Indo Board</a> , a 30-inch by 18-inch balance trainer that can be replaced with a plank of wood of similar dimensions. Place the board atop the BOSU. Step your left foot forward while keeping your right foot back until you feel balanced. Keep your gaze forward. This might be enough of a challenge. If you feel stable, bend your knees into a squat and reach the left hand down to the front of the board. Slowly return to the starting position. Perform 10 to 12 squats on each side one to two times.<br> <strong>Option:</strong> If you are new to balance training, you can perform this exercise on the floor in a split stance, reaching hand to opposite foot. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/129ada90-0ec8-46ba-9d4c-6163a04f16af.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Jen Murphy at <a href="mailto:workout@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">workout@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/exercises-paddleboard-balance-5e0fdcbb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/exercises-paddleboard-balance-5e0fdcbb<author><![CDATA[Jen Murphy]]></author><category> photo-commission</category><category> wsjlifework</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Physical/Mental Fitness</category><category> Health</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Suzie Cooney</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>physical</category><category> mental fitness</category><category> health</category><category> living</category><category> lifestyle </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Did Elon Musk Really Just Go There? The Long History Behind His Bawdy Humor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> This week&#39;s spat with Mark Zuckerberg highlights Musk&#39;s flirtation with blue jokes that has both helped and hindered him <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056943"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817758?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Elon Musk has built a following with wink-wink high-jinks at the companies he runs.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Paul Hennessy/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001056943"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tim-higgins" itemprop="url" rel="author">Tim Higgins</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 15, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/did-elon-musk-really-just-go-there-the-long-history-behind-his-bawdy-humor-f1da4a11"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The man <em>has</em> devoted much of his life to building giant rockets.</p><p> So, perhaps, it should be no surprise that it has come to this: <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk</a> resorting to phallic barbs in his online feud with fellow billionaire Mark Zuckerberg.</p><p> “I propose a literal dick measuring contest,” <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1678222776908275712?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">Musk tweeted</a> last Sunday night, topping even himself for a new level of blatant crassness.</p><p> His coarse banter on a very public stage stands in stark contrast to much of corporate America&#39;s current state of heartburn over possibly triggering any offense. After watching Bud Light <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bud-light-boycott-sales-dylan-mulvaney-6c23bb86?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fumble with transgender issues</a> , c-suite executives have increased trepidation over <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bud-light-controversy-illustrates-heightened-risks-for-brands-that-touch-on-sociopolitical-topics-9625f3cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">being associated with social topics</a> —even ones that may have recently been seen as promoting social good—out of concern about falling within someone&#39;s crosshairs.</p><p> Not Musk. He has built a following with wink-wink high-jinks at the companies he runs, from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">Tesla</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the car company; to SpaceX, the rocket maker; and, as of late October, Twitter, the social-media platform.</p><p> Some Twitter users found his Zuckerberg zinger out of bounds, such as Emmet Peppers, a hedge-fund manager, <a href="https://twitter.com/EmmetPeppers/status/1678464559550722048?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">who responded</a> : “Come on man…probably should delete this one.”</p><p> For many others—more than 55,000 users liked the tweet as of Friday evening—the jab appealed to a certain sophomoric sensibility, helping explain the unusual populism that Musk, as the world&#39;s richest man, has cultivated after more than a decade of unusual tweeting.</p><p> Over the years, his jokes have only grown edgier. Years ago, it was about naming Tesla&#39;s vehicles so the ending characters on the model monikers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-desire-for-s-e-x-leads-to-confusion-with-model-3-1493892001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">spelled out S.3.XY</a> Today, he <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1637420728743088130?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">automatically responds</a> to press inquiries at Twitter with poop emojis. His antics, even if off-putting to some, have helped endear him to others, who say he seems more authentic compared with image-conscious CEOs at other companies.</p><p> Musk&#39;s sense of humor was on display in 2021 when he appeared as host of NBC&#39;s “Saturday Night Live,” making jokes about himself, Gen Z and dogecoin.他还打扮成超级马里奥兄弟。主要对手瓦里奥。</p><p> With almost 150 million Twitter followers, Musk&#39;s public stage may be bigger than most, although he isn&#39;t the first business leader to try to harness the power of humor, which done successfully can create delight and foster connections.</p><p> Among the most notable is Warren Buffett, who has long peppered his shareholder letters with aw-shucks humor. In 2008, the Oracle of Omaha <a href="https://www.berkshirehathaway.com/letters/2007ltr.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">cited country music lyrics</a> to sum up the challenges of buying companies: “I&#39;ve never gone to bed with an ugly woman, but I&#39;ve sure woke up with a few.”</p><p> Yet Musk&#39;s style is riskier, especially as he toys with topics not universally seen as funny such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-compares-justin-trudeau-to-hitler-in-since-deleted-tweet-11645130462?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Hitler</a> , <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1527344969471520768?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">mansplaining</a> or <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1321275062998257665?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">sperm banks</a> . And at times, some have viewed Musk&#39;s comments as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-twitter-flame-throwing-has-new-magnitude-11671100283?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">going too far</a> , veering into <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-apologizes-for-calling-british-cave-explorer-a-pedophile-1531904504?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hurtful attacks</a> and sexist tropes.</p><p> Last year, for example, he made light of an Insider report that <strong>&nbsp;</strong> SpaceX had settled claims by a flight attendant that included an accusation Musk had exposed himself to her. The billionaire took to Twitter <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1527496917579612161?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">to call the allegations “utterly untrue</a> ” and went into joke mode. “Finally, we get to use Elongate as scandal name,” <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1527525498460508160?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">he tweeted</a> . “这有点完美。”</p><p> Employees later complained, in an open letter to SpaceX executives, that his public antics, including that tweet in particular, were a distraction. The group cited more than a couple dozen of Musk&#39;s tweets between 2020 and 2022 that it said “clearly depict the &#39;Bro culture&#39; Elon seems to not only tolerate, but embrace and encourage online and in his personal life.”</p><p> Also among their list of offending tweets: <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1453954994546229253?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">One Musk sent</a> during an October night in 2021 that was aimed at those who were wise to spelling humor: “Am thinking of starting new university: Texas Institute of Technology &amp; Science.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>What do you think about Elon Musk&#39;s sense of humor? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> It wasn&#39;t lost on certain followers that the made-up school name&#39;s acronym was a certain vulgar slang for the female anatomy. “It will have epic merch,” Musk added in follow-up tweets. “Universally admired.”</p><p> Swiftly, Musk faced criticism as being a chauvinist, especially as the tech industry broadly struggles with accusations of misogyny within its male-dominated ranks.</p><p> “As a shareholder and customer, this is really a puzzling and disappointing attempt at humor,” <a href="https://twitter.com/EricWenger/status/1454302230543224835?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">responded Eric Wenger</a> , an executive at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSCO" class="">Cisco</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> “We are trying to encourage more women to pursue technology degrees and careers. I cannot see how this helps that effort in any way.”</p><p> In following months, Tesla faced a string of lawsuits, unrelated to Musk&#39;s comments, by women claiming sexual harassment at the automaker&#39;s Bay Area assembly plant. “Tesla has subjected women working in its Fremont plant to nightmarish conditions of rampant sexual harassment,” a lawsuit filed by one of the women said.</p><p> The automaker didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment on the continuing cases. It has said it is against any kinds of harassment or discrimination.</p><p> Musk saves some of his most pointed, blue retorts for fellow billionaires—as if he is trying to rattle them or define them publicly on his own terms.</p><p> After billionaire <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/jeff-bezos">Jeff Bezos</a> &#39; rocket company Blue Origin in 2021 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bezos-blue-origin-rebuffed-in-its-protest-of-moon-lander-contract-11627670119" target="_blank" class="icon none">protested a government contract</a> being <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nasa-picks-spacex-to-build-new-lunar-lander-11618604869?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">awarded to Space X</a> , Musk <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1386825367948644352?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">responded on Twitter</a> that his rival, “Can&#39;t get it up (to orbit) lol.”</p><p> Then last year, Musk, who has claimed Bill Gates was short selling Tesla stock, <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1517707521343082496?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">posted a tweet</a> of the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">Microsoft</a> co-founder in an unflattering profile picture in which he compared him with a pregnant-man emoji and wrote, “in case u need to lose a boner fast.”</p><p> The latest beef with Zuckerberg emerged as the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a> CEO <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/zuckerberg-channeled-og-mark-to-fast-track-secret-effort-that-became-threads-86ce532e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">prepared to launch a rival app to Twitter</a> . In the lead up to its debut last week, Musk had already <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-fight-b71fa4ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">proposed a cage fight</a> between the two, but his pokes became more lewd after Zuckerberg&#39;s Threads was greeted with a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-zuckerberg-threads-twitter-elon-musk-ecec1eaa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">wave of positive publicity</a> amid struggles at Twitter.</p><p> Hours after Sunday&#39;s tweet proposing the bawdy measuring contest, Musk <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1678280654578933761?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">posted something</a> akin to a PSA for Twitter: “You will get more laughs from this app than everything combined.”</p><p> “But I have to warn you,” Musk added, “don&#39;t be shocked…there&#39;s some negative stuff too.”</p><p> Write to Tim Higgins at <a href="mailto:tim.higgins@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">tim.higgins@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/did-elon-musk-really-just-go-there-the-long-history-behind-his-bawdy-humor-f1da4a11</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/did-elon-musk-really-just-go-there-the-long-history-behind-his-bawdy-humor-f1da4a11<author><![CDATA[Tim Higgins]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category> Market Research/Public Relations</category><category> Public Relations</category><category> Advertising/Marketing/Public Relations</category><category> Business/Consumer Services</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>High Net Worth Individuals</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Meta Platforms</category><category> META</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>high net worth individuals</category><category> market research</category><category> public relations</category><category> advertising</category><category> marketing</category><category> business</category><category> consumer services</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Economists Are Cutting Back Their Recession Expectations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Forecasters still expect GDP to eventually contract, but later, and by less, than previously <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055544"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816824?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Labor Department&#39;s consumer-price index is sharply lower than the peak in June 2022 and the slowest in more than two years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Joe Raedle/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055544"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/harriet-torry" itemprop="url" rel="author">Harriet Torry</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anthony-debarros" itemprop="url" rel="author">Anthony DeBarros</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 15, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-are-cutting-back-their-recession-expectations-74118938"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Economists are dialing back recession risks.</p><p> Easing inflation, a still-strong labor market and economic resilience led business and academic economists polled by The Wall Street Journal to lower the probability of a recession in the next 12 months to 54% from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-turn-more-pessimistic-on-inflation-ed2fd667?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">61% in the prior two surveys</a> .</p><p> While that probability is still high by historical comparison, it represents the largest month-over-month percentage-point drop since August 2020, as the economy was recovering from a short but sharp recession induced by the Covid-19 pandemic. It reflects the fact that the economy has kept growing even as the Federal Reserve has raised interest rates and inflation declined. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815625?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> In the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/economic-forecasting-survey-archive-11617814998?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">latest WSJ survey</a> , economists expected gross domestic product to have grown at a 1.5% annual rate in the second quarter, a sharp uptick from 0.2% in the previous survey.他们仍然预计 GDP 最终会收缩，但会比之前收缩得更晚，而且收缩幅度也较小。他们预计第三季度经济将增长 0.6%，而之前调查中预计经济将收缩 0.3%，第四季度经济将收缩 0.1%。预测人士表示，从去年第四季度开始计算，2023 年 GDP 将增长 1%，是之前预测的 0.5% 的两倍。</p><p> Nearly 60% of economists said their main reason for optimism about the economic outlook is their expectation that inflation will continue to slow. The Labor Department&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">consumer-price index</a> climbed 3% in June from a year earlier, sharply lower than the peak of 9.1% in June 2022 and the slowest in more than two years.美联储首选的通胀指标——不包括食品和能源的个人消费支出价格指数的年度变化——已从2022年3月的5.4%降至5月的4.6%。 Economists expect it to reach 3.7% by the fourth quarter of this year, though that is still well above the Fed&#39;s 2% target.</p><h3> Pathway to a soft landing</h3><p> Many economists first began in the middle of last year to project a recession when persistently high inflation prompted the Fed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-raises-rates-by-0-75-percentage-point-largest-increase-since-1994-11655316170?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">raise rates at the most aggressive pace</a> in nearly three decades.从历史上看，大幅降低通胀率总是会带来更高的失业率和经济衰退，很少有经济学家认为这一次会有所不同。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>Are you still worried about a recession?为什么或者为什么不？ Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> Now, a pathway to achieve a “soft landing,” or getting inflation down without a recession, is “back on the table,” said Sean Snaith, the director of the University of Central Florida&#39;s Institute for Economic Forecasting. “今年年初，这似乎更像是一个白日梦，”斯奈思说。现在，“经济衰退似乎正在不断滑落、滑落、滑向未来。” Snaith has lowered the probability of recession to 45% from 90% in April. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815972?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> On average, economists still expect the labor market will lose 10,551 jobs a month in the first quarter of 2024, broadly unchanged from their previous forecast.但与四月份的调查不同的是，经济学家不再预计今年第三和第四季度会出现裁员。他们预计雇主将在明年第二和第三季度增加就业岗位，这表明经济衰退将是温和的。</p><p> “Inflation has slowed remarkably already, and we believe will continue to do so because spending growth is slowing substantially and the growth in labor force is helping service providers,” said Luke Tilley, chief economist at Wilmington Trust.</p><p> Still, stronger-than-expected economic growth this year will also likely result in the Fed keeping interest rates higher for longer, according to the Journal survey.</p><p> Economists expected the midpoint of the range for the federal-funds rate will peak at 5.4% in December, up sharply from a 5% forecast in the last survey.最新预测意味着美联储至少还会加息 25 个基点。</p><h3> More rate increases, later rate cuts</h3><p> The Fed last month <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-holds-rates-steady-but-expects-more-increases-b1be87f2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">held its benchmark federal-funds rate steady</a> in a range between 5% and 5.25%, its first pause after 10 consecutive increases since March 2022. Market participants overwhelmingly expect the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-fed-debate-this-month-what-would-prompt-a-rate-hike-this-fall-a7e9f83e?mod=djemRTE_h" target="_blank" class="icon none">central bank will raise rates</a> by a quarter-percentage point at its July 25-26 meeting, according to the federal-funds futures market. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1400" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817618?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Economists are also pushing back their estimates for when the Fed will eventually start cutting rates.在最新的调查中，只有10.6%的经济学家预计今年下半年会降息，低于上次调查的36.8%。大多数经济学家（近79%）预计，随着失业率上升，美联储将在2024年上半年降息。 Some 42.4% expected that first cut will come in the second quarter.</p><p> Economists are relatively sanguine about the impact of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/student-loan-repayments-deadline-economy-913acc34?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the end of the government&#39;s pandemic-era pause</a> on student-debt payments, which allowed millions of Americans to avoid a big monthly bill for more than three years.</p><p> The resumption of student-loan payments is expected to have a relatively minor impact this fall, shaving 0.2 percentage points, annualized, from consumer spending growth, measured from the third quarter to the fourth quarter of this year.</p><p> “We will likely see some slowing in spending growth toward the end of this year as a result of the resumed payments denting certain households&#39; ability to consume, but we do not think the end to the payment pause will be widespread enough to have a significant effect on overall US household spending,” said <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WFC" class="company-name">Wells Fargo</a> chief economist</p> Jay Bryson.<p></p><p> The survey of 69 economists was conducted July 7-12. Not every economist answered every question.</p><p> Write to Harriet Torry at <a href="mailto:harriet.torry@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">harriet.torry@wsj.com</a> and Anthony DeBarros at <a href="mailto:anthony.debarros@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anthony.debarros@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-are-cutting-back-their-recession-expectations-74118938</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-are-cutting-back-their-recession-expectations-74118938<author><![CDATA[Harriet TorryAnthony DeBarros]]></author><category> inflation</category><category> Contracts/Orders</category><category> Non-Government Contracts/Orders</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category> Economic Growth/Recession</category><category> Monetary Policy</category><category> Interest Rates</category><category> Economic News</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>Economic Predictions/Forecasts</category><category> Surveys/Polls</category><category> Inflation</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> contracts</category><category> orders</category><category> non-government contracts</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category> economic growth</category><category> recession</category><category> monetary policy</category><category> interest rates</category><category> economic news</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>economic predictions</category><category> forecasts</category><category> surveys</category><category> polls </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Talkin’ ’Bout Our Generations: How They Shape (Almost) Everything in 2023]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Are you a boomer? Millennial? A member of Gen Z or X? ​As this collection of 20 stories explores, the ways we eat, dress, travel and scroll all depend a lot on when we were born. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-815929/?width=1080&amp;size=0.8" alt="BORN IN A TRUNK Please note that our member of the Silent Generation was agile enough to climb to the top of this family tree." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> BORN IN A TRUNK Please note that our member of the Silent Generation was agile enough to climb to the top of this family tree. Jack Hudson <span>Jack Hudson</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055285"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001055285"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">WSJ Off Duty Editors</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 15, 2023 12:21 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/talkin-bout-our-generations-how-they-shape-our-style-our-vacations-and-why-were-us-aaece027"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p class="has-drop-cap"> <strong>WHY PUT</strong> together a special editorial package all about generations? It&#39;s simple: In 2023, no one can shut up about the ever-shifting dynamics between young and old—especially when it comes to trends. Flip phones? Those mature enough to remember the devices&#39; first coming can&#39;t quite fathom why Gen Z has embraced them. Ditto: those plastic “claws” used to fashion cockatoo-like hairstyles first seen in the &#39;80s.</p><p> As boomers ease deeper into retirement, their dominance waning, and Gen X (the “forgotten generation”) toils in obscurity, millennials—now entering their 40s—have seen their role as the-ones-who-get-all-headlines usurped by Gen Z. Avocado toast, so central to millennials&#39; image, seems as dusty and irrelevant as a Victrola.</p><p> Still, what we learned in gathering these 20 stories is that every generation has lessons to offer the others. That won&#39;t stop the young from masterminding exciting, toast-based innovations (the ball&#39;s in your court, Gen Z) or older Americans from (understandably) rolling their eyes.</p><p> But it&#39;s a start. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
